 Here is some basic code to make an application runnable in Java:

```java
public class MyApp {

  public static void main(String[] args) {

    // Create a new instance of the application
    MyApp app = new MyApp();

    // Run the application
    app.run();

  }

  public void run() {
    // Application logic goes here
  }

}
```

To break this down:

- The MyApp class contains the main method, which is the entry point for a Java application. 

- The main method creates a new instance of MyApp and calls its run() method.

- The run() method contains the core application logic. This is where you would put the actual code for your program.

- The main method and run() method are marked as public and static where appropriate. This allows the JVM to call them properly.

- The class and methods have no package declaration, so they are part of the default package.

So in summary, this provides a simple template for a runnable Java application with a main entry point and a custom run() method where you can add your own logic. You would then compile and execute this class to launch your application.
